Implement a RESTful API endpoint using Spring Boot that processes a JSON payload and returns a filtered list of items from an in-memory data source. The API should accept HTTP POST requests. Your tasks are as follows:

  1. Setup: Assume you have a Spring Boot application already set up with the necessary dependencies to implement a RESTful service.

  2. Endpoint Definition: Create a POST endpoint /filterItems that will take a JSON payload as input.

  3. Input Format: The JSON payload will contain the following structure:

    JSON
    Copy code
    {
  "filterCondition": "string"
}

    The filterCondition will specify the substring that items must contain to be included in the result.

  4. Data Source: Use the following predefined list of string items as your in-memory data source:

    Java
    Copy code
    List<String> items = Arrays.asList("apple", "banana", "apricot", "blueberry", "orange");

  5. Filter Logic: Implement the logic to filter this list based on whether each item contains the filterCondition substring.

  6. Output Format: The response should be a JSON array of filtered strings that satisfy the condition. If no items match, return an empty array.

  7. Assumptions and Constraints:

    • The filterCondition is case-sensitive.
    • The list of items to be filtered is provided in-memory and not retrieved from an external source.
    • You do not need to handle empty or missing filterCondition fields; assume it's always present in the input.

  8. Example:

    • Input JSON: { "filterCondition": "ap" }
    • Expected Output: ["apple", "apricot"]

Implement the solution using appropriate Spring Boot best practices, ensuring your code is clean and well-organized. Consider edge cases where applicable, but focus primarily on the core functionality within the given time constraints.

Question 2.1

You are tasked to create a stored procedure in your choice of SQL dialect (e.g., MySQL or Postgres). This stored procedure should filter and summarize user data from a users table. The table contains the following columns:

  • id: An integer representing the unique identifier of the user.
  • name: A string representing the name of the user.
  • age: An integer representing the age of the user.
  • email: A string representing the email address of the user.
  • country: A string representing the country where the user resides.

Requirements:

  1. Your stored procedure should take the following input parameters:

    • min_age: An integer specifying the minimum age of users to be included.
    • max_age: An integer specifying the maximum age of users to be included.
    • country: A string specifying the country of users to be included.

  2. The stored procedure should output the following summary report:

    • total_user_count: An integer representing the number of users who fall between min_age and max_age and reside in the specified country.
    • average_user_age: A float representing the average age of users who meet the criteria.

  3. If no users meet the specified criteria, the procedure should return zero for the total_user_count and NULL for the average_user_age.

  4. Ensure that your stored procedure can handle the scenario where some input parameters are missing (e.g., the caller might only specify min_age and country, but not max_age). In such cases, provide functional defaults. For example, use the highest age in the users table as the default max_age if it is not specified by the caller.

  5. It should not rely on any external libraries or frameworks.

Sample Data (for reference):

id name age email country
1 Alice 28 alice@example.com USA
2 Bob 24 bob@example.com USA
3 Charlie 32 charlie@example.com Canada
4 Diana 35 diana@example.com USA
5 Eva 29 eva@example.com Canada

Evaluation Criteria:

  • The correctness of the stored procedure: Does it correctly filter based on age and country, and return the requested outputs?
  • Handling of input parameters: Does it handle cases where some parameters are not provided?
  • Efficient use of SQL features: Are SQL features optimally used to achieve the task efficiently?
  • Code readability and organization: Is the code simple to read and well-organized?
Candidate's answer

Copy code
1-- postgresql 2CREATE FUNCTION filter_users_summary( 3 minAge INT, 4 maxAge INT DEFAULT NULL, 5 country_filter VARCHAR DEFAULT NULL 6) 7RETURNS TABLE( 8 totalCount INT, 9 avgAge NUMERIC 10) 11AS $$ 12DECLARE 13 tmpMaxAge INT; 14BEGIN 15 IF maxAge IS NULL THEN 16 SELECT MAX(age) INTO tmpMaxAge FROM users; 17 maxAge := tmpMaxAge; 18 END IF; 19 20 RETURN QUERY 21 SELECT 22 COUNT(*)::INT AS totalCount, 23 ROUND(AVG(age)::NUMERIC, 2) AS avgAge 24 FROM users 25 WHERE age BETWEEN minAge AND maxAge 26 AND (country_filter IS NULL OR country = country_filter); 27 28END; 29$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;
Review & Evaluation
AI review

Correctness: The procedure is mostly correct; it implements the required filtering logic with parameters for minAge, maxAge (defaulting to NULL), and country (defaulting to NULL), and summarizes the count and average age as required. If maxAge is not supplied, it is set to the highest age found in the users table, which meets the requirement for functional defaults. If no users match, COUNT(*) returns 0 and AVG(age) returns NULL, fitting the specification.

Readability: The code is readable, clearly structured, and leverages PL/pgSQL effectively, using RETURN QUERY and parameter handling.

Performance: Efficient, there's a single-pass aggregate over the filtered data, so performance is as good as possible for this query.

Completeness: The solution is almost complete but not perfect: The handling of 'country' as NULL is not exactly per the requirement. In the requirements, 'country' is supposed to be a required parameter, not an optional one. Allowing NULL for country would mean returning the summary for all countries, which is not what the problem specifies. The requirement is 'the specified country' rather than 'optionally filter by country'. If the intent was to allow all-countries summary with a NULL input, that's fine, but it's not clearly indicated as such in the question. (Otherwise, this may be minor.) Also, parameter names should match the spec (min_age, max_age, country) and it's preferable to document expected units and behaviors clearly.

Depth: Shows senior handling of default logic, but could comment about concurrency (what happens if SELECT MAX(age) returns NULL, or the users table is empty?), though this is minor. Could enforce NOT NULL for country, per spec, and add parameter name consistency.

Final: A strong answer, just short of full marks due to a slight ambiguity in how the 'country' parameter is handled regarding NULL, and minor cleanliness in parameter names.

Theory Discussion: Design Patterns and Software Principles

Discuss the potential benefits and drawbacks of using the Singleton and Factory design patterns while coding in Java. Provide clear and concise explanations to illustrate the theoretical and practical differences between these two patterns.

  1. Singleton Design Pattern:

    • Explain what the Singleton pattern is and the typical situation in which it is used. Discuss key characteristics of the pattern.
    • Discuss its benefits, such as efficiency and controlled access to resources.
    • Discuss potential drawbacks, such as testing challenges and code maintainability.
    • Provide an example scenario in which using a Singleton pattern would be advantageous, outlining why it suits the situation.

  2. Factory Design Pattern:

    • Explain what the Factory pattern is, along with an overview of its purpose in object-oriented design.
    • Discuss its benefits, including flexibility and system decoupling.
    • Address its potential drawbacks, like added complexity and potential overengineering.
    • Present an example scenario where the Factory pattern would be effectively employed, justifying its selection for the scenario.

Your answer should clearly contrast the roles and impacts of these patterns in a broader software architecture perspective and may include theoretical scenarios or simplified pseudo-code to illustrate uses. Ensure that your discussion is rooted in typical object-oriented programming principles.

11. The Singleton design pattern is a way to ensure that a class has only one instance throughout the application's lifecycle. Instead of creating multiple objects, you simply reuse the same object. 2 3Pros: 4 - Resource Efficiency: It allows for efficient management and sharing of finite resources like database connections 5 - Instance control: Singleton prevents other objects from instantiating their own copies of the Singleton object, ensuring that all objects access the single instance. 6 - Flexibility: Since the class controls the instantiation process, the class has the flexibility to change the instantiation process. 7Cons: 8 - They are generally used as a global instance. You have been provided with a partial Java application developed using Spring Boot, implementing an MVC architecture. Your task is to review this code snippet, identify any violations of MVC principles, and suggest improvements to adhere to proper MVC design patterns. Focus on separation of concerns, appropriate responsibilities for each component (Model, View, Controller), and adherence to best practices in Spring Boot application development.

Java
Copy code
// Sample code snippet of a Java MVC application using Spring Boot

@Controller
public class UserController {
    // This service dependency is expected to manage business logic
    private final UserService userService;
    
    @Autowired
    public UserController(UserService userService) {
        this.userService = userService;
    }

    // This method handles user data fetching and rendering
    @GetMapping("/users")
    public String getAllUsers(Model model) {
        List<User> users = userService.getAllUsers();
        long totalActiveUsers = users.stream().filter(User::isActive).count();
        model.addAttribute("users", users);
        model.addAttribute("totalActiveUsers", totalActiveUsers);
        
        return "userListView";
    }

    // Method to handle new user creation
    @PostMapping("/users")
    public String createUser(String username, String email) {
        User newUser = new User();
        newUser.setUsername(username);
        newUser.setEmail(email);

        userService.saveUser(newUser);
        
        return "redirect:/users";
    }
}

@Service
public class UserService {
    private final UserRepository userRepository;

    @Autowired
    public UserService(UserRepository userRepository) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
    }

    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }

    public void saveUser(User user) {
        userRepository.save(user);
    }
}

Task

  1. Identify Violations: Analyze the provided code to identify at least two violations of MVC principles.
  2. Explain Violations: Clearly explain why each identified case is a violation of MVC principles or best practices.
  3. Suggest Improvements: Provide concrete improvements or refactor suggestions to fix the identified issues and explain how these changes help to adhere to the MVC pattern.

Evaluation Criteria

  • Clarity and Depth of Analysis: How well did you identify and explain the issues present in the code?
  • Applicability of Suggestions: Are the suggested improvements practical and align with MVC principles?
  • Understanding of MVC Principles: Demonstrated understanding of MVC patterns through analysis and improvement suggestions.

Assumptions

  • The code is part of a typical Spring Boot application using the MVC framework.
  • Candidates should not assume any other portions of the application exist beyond the provided snippet.
  • Focus is on adhering to separation of concerns within the MVC framework.

Task

  1. Write a Groovy class MWayTree that represents an M-Way Tree with the following functionalities:

    • Constructor to initialize the tree with a specified maximum number of children m per node.
    • A method insert(key) to insert a new key into the M-Way Tree while maintaining the properties of the tree.

  2. Discuss any features of Groovy that make your implementation different from how you might implement the same functionality in Java.

Assumptions

  • We are working with an integer-only M-Way Tree.
  • The M-Way Tree should maintain sorted order of keys at each node.
  • Assume that the value of m will be greater than or equal to 3.
  • No need to handle duplicate keys; each key is unique.

Constraints

  • You should not use any external libraries. Use only core Groovy capabilities.
  • Clearly comment on how state changes when a new key is inserted.
  • Provide clear explanatory comments about any Groovy-specific syntax or idioms used.

Sample Data

  • The initial tree is empty. Insert the following keys in order: [10, 20, 5, 6, 7, 8, 30, 15, 40].

Evaluation Criteria

  • Correctness: The M-Way Tree should maintain the correct structure after each insertion.
  • Groovy Usage: Appropriately leverage Groovys language features in your implementation.
  • Code Quality: Clear and well-commented code with meaningful variable and method names.

Begin by writing the MWayTree class constructor, then implement the insert method and finally document the Groovy features used. Remember to focus on efficiency and clarity in your solution.
